# Cursor Rules for RCI Manager Frontend

## Contract Overview

- React 18 + TypeScript
- Vite as build tool
- Shadcn/UI component library with Radix UI primitives
- Tailwind CSS for styling
- React Router DOM for routing
- React Hook Form + Zod for form handling and validation
- TanStack Query for data fetching
- Lucide React for icons

## Code Style & Standards

### TypeScript

- Use TypeScript for all new files (.tsx for React components, .ts for utilities)
- Prefer type inference over explicit typing when obvious
- Use interfaces for object shapes and types for unions/primitives
- Follow the existing TypeScript configuration (strict mode disabled)
- Use path aliases `@/` for src imports

### React Components

- Use functional components with hooks
- Use React.forwardRef for components that need ref forwarding
- Prefer arrow functions for inline handlers
- Use proper TypeScript typing for props (extend HTML element props when needed)
- Follow the Shadcn/UI pattern for component composition

### Styling

- Use Tailwind CSS classes exclusively for styling
- Follow the existing design system with CSS variables for colors
- Use the `cn()` utility function (from @/lib/utils) for conditional classes
- Prefer Tailwind utility classes over custom CSS
- Use the existing color palette defined in tailwind.config.ts

### Component Structure

```tsx
import React from "react";
import { cn } from "@/lib/utils";

interface ComponentProps extends React.HTMLAttributes<HTMLDivElement> {
  variant?: "default" | "secondary";
  // other props
}

const Component = React.forwardRef<HTMLDivElement, ComponentProps>(
  ({ className, variant = "default", ...props }, ref) => {
    return (
      <div
        ref={ref}
        className={cn("base-classes", variantClasses[variant], className)}
        {...props}
      />
    );
  }
);
Component.displayName = "Component";

export { Component };
```

### File Organization

- Use kebab-case for file and folder names
- Place components in appropriate directories:
  - `src/components/ui/` for reusable UI components (Shadcn/UI)
  - `src/components/layout/` for layout components
  - `src/components/[feature]/` for feature-specific components
  - `src/pages/` for page components
  - `src/lib/` for utilities and configurations
  - `src/hooks/` for custom hooks
  - `src/types/` for type definitions

### Imports

- Use absolute imports with `@/` alias
- Group imports in this order:
  1. React and external libraries
  2. Internal utilities and types
  3. Components (UI first, then feature components)
  4. Relative imports
- Use named imports for Lucide React icons
- Prefer default imports for React and main libraries

### Forms

- Use React Hook Form with Zod validation
- Use the form components from Shadcn/UI
- Follow this pattern:

```tsx
import { useForm } from "react-hook-form";
import { zodResolver } from "@hookform/resolvers/zod";
import { z } from "zod";

const formSchema = z.object({
  field: z.string().min(1, "Field is required"),
});

type FormData = z.infer<typeof formSchema>;

const MyForm = () => {
  const form = useForm<FormData>({
    resolver: zodResolver(formSchema),
    defaultValues: {
      field: "",
    },
  });

  const onSubmit = (data: FormData) => {
    // handle submission
  };

  return (
    <Form {...form}>
      <form onSubmit={form.handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>{/* form fields */}</form>
    </Form>
  );
};
```

### Data Fetching

- Use TanStack Query (React Query) for server state management
- Create service functions in `src/lib/[feature]/service.ts`
- Use proper error handling and loading states
- Follow the existing pattern in the contracts service

### Naming Conventions

- Use PascalCase for components and types
- Use camelCase for variables, functions, and props
- Use SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for constants
- Use kebab-case for files and folders
- Use descriptive names that clearly indicate purpose

### Error Handling

- Use proper error boundaries for component errors
- Handle async errors gracefully with try-catch
- Provide meaningful error messages to users
- Use the toast system (Sonner) for user notifications

### Performance

- Use React.memo for expensive components when needed
- Prefer code splitting for large features
- Optimize images and assets
- Use proper dependency arrays in useEffect/useMemo/useCallback

### Testing & Quality

- Follow ESLint rules (ignore src/components/ui/\*\* as configured)
- Use TypeScript strict mode where possible
- Prefer composition over complex prop drilling
- Keep components focused and single-responsibility

### UI/UX Guidelines

- Follow the existing design patterns in the app
- Use consistent spacing with Tailwind classes
- Ensure responsive design with Tailwind breakpoints
- Maintain accessibility with proper ARIA attributes
- Use the existing icon library (Lucide React)
- Follow the dark mode implementation with next-themes

### Route Patterns

- Use React Router DOM v6 patterns
- Implement protected routes with the ProtectedRoute component
- Use proper route params typing
- Follow the existing page structure in src/pages/

## Code Examples

### Creating a New Page

```tsx
import { usePageTitle } from "@/hooks/use-page-title";

const MyPage = () => {
  usePageTitle("Page Title");

  return (
    <div className="container mx-auto py-6">
      <h1 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-6">Page Title</h1>
      {/* page content */}
    </div>
  );
};

export default MyPage;
```

### Creating a Feature Component

```tsx
import { Card, CardContent, CardHeader, CardTitle } from "@/components/ui/card";
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button";

interface FeatureComponentProps {
  title: string;
  onAction: () => void;
}

const FeatureComponent = ({ title, onAction }: FeatureComponentProps) => {
  return (
    <Card>
      <CardHeader>
        <CardTitle>{title}</CardTitle>
      </CardHeader>
      <CardContent>
        <Button onClick={onAction}>Action</Button>
      </CardContent>
    </Card>
  );
};

export { FeatureComponent };
```

## Best Practices

- Always use the existing component library (Shadcn/UI) before creating custom components
- Follow the established folder structure and naming conventions
- Use TypeScript types consistently throughout the codebase
- Implement proper loading states and error handling
- Keep components small and focused
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Maintain consistent code formatting with Prettier/ESLint
- Document complex logic with comments
- Use the existing utility functions and patterns
